04526nam a22005175i 9780773569676DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20022002xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735696767 a10.1515/97807735696762doi  a(DE-B1597)656384  a(OCoLC)1394872565  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aE99.C88bM679 2002eb 7aSOC0210002bisacsh04a971.4/110049731 aMorantz, Toby, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhite Man's Gonna Getcha :bThe Colonial Challenge to the Crees in Quebec /cToby Morantz. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2002] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (424 p.) :bIllustrations, maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Indigenous and Northern Studies ;v3000tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAppendices -- tAppendices -- tPreface -- tAuthor’s Note -- tIntroduction: Marking the Trails -- tJames Bay at the End of the Nineteenth Century -- tThe Powers of Religion: Christianity Extends the Limits -- tCoping with Changes on the Land -- tA New Technological and Bureaucratic World: The Confiscation of the Land -- tPale Versions of Southern Institutions -- tConclusion: Despite Government Domination, the Crees Weave Their Own Tapestry -- tEpilogue: A New Order -- tAppendix 1 -- tAppendix 2 -- tAppendix 3 -- tExamples of Department of Indian Affairs Reporting of Beaver Preserves -- tAppendix 5 -- tAppendix 6 -- tQuantities of Game Taken by Alfie Matoush Group, August 1953 to Early June 1954 -- tSubstantive Notes -- tReference Notes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMorantz shows that with the imposition of administration from the south the Crees had to confront a new set of foreigners whose ideas and plans were very different from those of the fur traders. In the 1930s and 1940s government intervention helped overcome the disastrous disappearance of the beaver through the creation of government-decreed preserves and a ban on beaver hunting, but beginning in the 1950s a revolving array of socio-economic programs instituted by the government brought the adverse effects of what Morantz calls bureaucratic colonialism. Drawing heavily on oral testimonies recorded by anthropologists in addition to eye-witness and archival sources, Morantz incorporates the Crees' own views, interests, and responses. She shows how their strong ties to the land and their appreciation of the wisdom of their way of life, coupled with the ineptness and excessive frugality of the Canadian bureaucracy, allowed them to escape the worst effects of colonialism. Despite becoming increasingly politically and economically dominated by Canadian society, the Crees succeeded in staving off cultural subjugation. They were able to face the massive hydroelectric development of the 1970s with their language, practices, and values intact and succeeded in negotiating a modern treaty. This detailed portrait of twentieth-century Canadian colonialism will be of interest to native studies specialists, anthropologists, and political scientists generally.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356967640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773569676423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773569676/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b201